{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:15:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:15:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16886"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16886"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.29,0.69,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67521"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9576"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52973"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22630"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67521"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cardiac action potential has a characteristic plateau phase that distinguishes it from action potentials in other excitable tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ionic basis of the cardiac action potential plateau phase?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sodium-potassium pump activity increasing membrane potential","Rapid sodium influx through voltage-gated channels","Calcium efflux balanced by sodium influx","Balanced inward calcium and outward potassium currents","Outward chloride current balanced by potassium efflux"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cardiac action potential plateau phase (phase 2) is maintained by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebalanced inward calcium and outward potassium currents\u003C/strong\u003E. During this phase, L-type calcium channels allow calcium entry while specific potassium channels permit potassium efflux. This balance maintains the membrane potential at a relatively constant level for approximately 200 milliseconds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid sodium influx through voltage-gated channels\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs during phase 0 (rapid depolarization), not the plateau phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOutward chloride current balanced by potassium efflux\u003C/strong\u003E - Chloride currents do not play a major role in the cardiac action potential plateau\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium-potassium pump activity increasing membrane potential\u003C/strong\u003E - The sodium-potassium pump maintains resting potential but does not contribute significantly to the plateau phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium efflux balanced by sodium influx\u003C/strong\u003E - During the plateau phase, calcium flows inward, not outward\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe plateau phase is crucial for cardiac function as it prolongs the refractory period, preventing premature contractions and allowing complete ventricular contraction before the next action potential can occur.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cardiac action potential plateau phase (phase 2) is maintained by balanced inward calcium and outward potassium currents.","L-type calcium channels allow calcium entry during the plateau phase, which triggers calcium-induced calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.","The plateau phase delays repolarization, ensuring complete ventricular contraction before the next action potential can occur."],"references":["Boron WF, Boulpaep EL. Medical physiology. 3rd ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52973"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16886"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52973"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T16:27:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T16:31:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9576"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67521"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt"